Solution — Exercise 06: Valgrind Invalid Read
===============================================

Step 1: Run with Valgrind
  valgrind --leak-check=full ./target

Step 2: Read the report
  Invalid read of size 4
    at sum_array (target.c:15)     ← total += arr[i++] when i == 5
    by main (target.c:29)
    Address is 0 bytes after a block of size 20 alloc'd
    at malloc (vg_replace_malloc.c:...)
    by main (target.c:21)

Answers:
  - Distance past allocation: 0 bytes after the end (i.e. the very next word)
  - Line: 15 — the loop body executing when i == 5
  - Correct condition: i < size (not i <= size)

The fix:
  while (i < size)
    total += arr[i++];

Why it matters:
  Buffer overreads are silent at runtime — the program often produces
  a plausible result and exits cleanly. But reading past a buffer can
  leak adjacent memory contents: other variables, heap metadata,
  or even sensitive data like keys or passwords.
  This is exactly the class of bug behind the Heartbleed vulnerability (CVE-2014-0160).

Step 3: Read the flag with GDB
  The flag is a static variable inside sum_array().
  gdb ./target
  (gdb) break sum_array
  (gdb) run
  (gdb) print flag
  → $1 = "HRZ{one_too_many}"

